NAME-
_printf : function that print a string in the standard output

SYNOPSIS-
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);

DESCRIPTION-

You can use specifiers of conversion,
you can specify what you want to convert in the arguments in the right order.

Specifiers of Conversion possible:

%c = print the char linked to it in the arguments
%s = print the char * linked to it in the arguments
%d = print the int linked to it in the arguments
%i = print the int linked to it in the arguments
%% = print the character '%'

Flags supported:

NONE

Field width :

None

Precision :

None

Lenght Modifiers:

None

RETURN VALUE-

The return value correspond to the numbers of bytes print in the
standard output. The NULL byte is not counted.
If the string in the argument is NULL, the function return a negative value.

EXAMPLES-

You may want to use _printf to print a date at the format
"Wednesday 22 july 2025" :
_printf("%s %d %s %d", day, date, month, year);

Another usage can be :
"The first letter of my name is A and I am 8"
_printf("The first letter of my name is %c and I am %i", FirstLetter, age);

SEE ALSO-

printf(3)

